details.purpose: To record measurements from an acoustic reflex test, and their interpretation by a clnician.
details.use:
Use to record measurements from a single acoustic reflext test, for diagnostic or screening purposes. Ipsilateral testing, contralateral testing or both, can be recorded per test ear.
Use to record the interpretation of all measurements for each single ear test configuration, and an overall interpretation (or audiological diagnosis).
Acoustic reflexes measure the eardrum movement generated by the stapedius and tensor tympani reflex in response to intense sound. The acoustic reflex threshold can be helpful in checking for particular types of hearing loss in situations where patient reliability is questionable. Acoustic reflex testing can also be done as part of a battery of tests to investigate central nervous system pathology, although this usage is now uncommon.

items.items: Record of measurements from an acoustic reflex test, and their clinical interpretation.
Default, unspecified point in time event which may be explicitly defined in a template or at run-time.
Identification of the acoustic reflex test performed.
The name of the test identifies the of type of stimulus used - either an acoustic or non acoustic stimulus.
Test of the reflex elicited from the stapedius muscle in response to an acoustic stimulus.
Test of the reflex elicited from the stapedius muscle in response to a non-acoustic stimulus e.g. tactile or orbital air-jet.
The test measurements and interpretations which can be recorded per ear, and includes ipsilateral and contralateral testing.
Identification of the ear to which the stimulus is presented and the ear where the probe is situated.
Stimulus presented to the left ear; probe is situated in left ear.
Stimulus presented to the right ear; probe is situated in right ear.
Stimulus presented to the left ear; probe is situated in right ear.
Stimulus presented to the right ear; probe is situated in left ear.
Reflex test that measures threshold levelss, reflex latency, reflex amplitude and reflex decay.
Reflex test that identifies the presence or absence of a reflex at a predetermined stimulation level.
The reflex has been observed as present.
The reflex has not been observed.
No screening test result is available for the test ear configuration.
Reason why no screening test result is available for the test ear configuration.
For example: ran out of time.
The lowest stimulation level at which a reflex could be measured by the probe.
Clinical interpretation of all diagnostic results for the specified test ear configuration.
Identification of the stimulation signal used for the test.
Noise with components over a wide range of frequencies.
Noise centred on a specified frequency.
A pure tone signal set at 500Hz.
A pure tone signal set at 1000Hz.
A pure tone signal set at 2000Hz.
A pure tone signal set at 4000Hz.
Length of time from onset of the stimulation tone to the onset of the middle ear muscle reflex.
Length of time that the reflex amplitude can be sustained.
No diagnostic test result is available for the test ear configuration.
Reason why no diagnostic test result is available for the test ear configuration.
Overall clinical interpretation of all of the results.
Coding with a terminology is preferred, where possible.
Clinical interpretation of reflex threshold during diagnostic testing, based on intensity.
Additional narrative about the test results and intepretation not captured in other fields.
Digital representation of the entire result.
Note: Multiple images can be recorded.
The intensity range in dB at which a reflex is expected in a normal hearing ear.
No reflex was elicited in response to a stimulation tone.
Reflex was elicited at an elevated stimulation level.
Clinical interpretation of reflex Threshold Level result based on sensation level.
Sensation level is the difference between the intensity of the stimulation tone and the patient's hearing threshold as measured on the audiogram.
The reflex was observed at a sensation level expected in a normal hearing ear.
The reflex was observed at a reduced sensation level compared to a normal hearing ear.
The reflex was observed at a higher sensation level than expected for a normal hearing ear.
No reflex was elecited in response to a stimulation tone.
Clinical interpretation of the screening test result.
Scale used for acoustic calibration of the test signal.
The test stimuli are calibrated using the sound pressure level scale.
The test stimuli are calibrated using the hearing level scale.
The criteria by which the Screening Assessment is passed.
These criteria are usually defined by authoritative guidelines, a central authority or by the local hearing program.
The loudness of the screening stimulus.
The frequency of the test signal.
The type of stimulation used to elicit a reflex.
Details of immittance machine used to conduct the test.
Description of incidental factors that may be contributing to the test result.
For example: The infant was crying at the time of testing.
Additional narrative about the method of testing not captured in other fields.
The frequency of the probe tone.
The probe tone frequency was set at 226Hz.
The probe tone frequency was set at 1000Hz.
Definition of the 'Normal Range' value specified within the Intensity data element used for Clinical Interpretation of the Diagnostic Test.
Additional information required to capture local content or to align with other reference models/formalisms.
For example: local information requirements or additional metadata to align with FHIR or CIMI equivalents.
